Introduction to this dataset¶

This soccer database comes from Kaggle and is well suited for data analysis and machine learning. It contains data for soccer matches, players, and teams from several European countries from 2008 to 2016. This dataset is quite extensive, and we encourage you to read more about it https://www.kaggle.com/hugomathien/soccer. ● The database is stored in a SQLite database file and contains several tables (Player, Player_attributes, Team, Team attributes). You can access database files using soware like DB Browser. ● This dataset will help you get good practice with your SQL joins. Make sure to look at how the dierent tables relate to each other. ● Some column titles should be self-explanatory, and others you’ll have to look up on Kaggle.

Posing Questions:¶

The following analysis will take look on the following questions
1)What are the attributes that affect to the players' overall quality?
2)What is the player that score the most penalities?

Read sqlite query results into a pandas DataFrame¶

The following function to get the specific table according to the query and convert it to datafram¶

In [4]:
def get_table_and_convert_to_dataframe(connection, query):
    """
        this function will retunr the table converted to datafram
        connection: the connection to database file
        query: the query which will get the sepcific table
    
    """
    return pd.read_sql_query(query, connection)
In [5]:
def scatter_plot(dataset, x, y, type_of_plot):
    dataset.plot(x=x, y=y, kind=type_of_plot);
In [6]:
def plot_histogram(dataset, feature):
    ax = dataset[feature].hist();
    ax.set_ylabel("Overall_Rating")
    ax.set_xlabel(feature)
    title = feature + " vs Overall_Rating"
    ax.set_title(title)
    print(pd.DataFrame(dataset[feature].describe()))

Conclusions¶

This dataset or database contains many tables which all of these tables represents a dataset itself, we depends on only 4 tables(datasets) which were Player, Player_Attributes, Team, Team_Attributes¶

To answer the two questions mentioned in the introduction of this project , I used only Player, and Player_Attributes.¶

I made some cleaning of those datasets, like hanlding missing values, duplicates¶

it seems that the most attributes that affect the overall rating of one player are (free_kick_accuracy , heading_accuracy, finishing, crossing) according to make scatter plots between each of these attributes against the overall_rating¶

we can gain more information from this database by check What teams improved the most over the time period? From 2008 to 2016¶

Limitations of this dataset:¶

1)Some of the attributes in Player_Attributes are categorical which are cannot be represented and these features affects the overall_rating
2)The dataset contains lots of tables which cannot be joined in visualizations
